  "summary": "Inspector Croome asserts that Sir Michael’s death was not a suicide, suggesting a killer scouted the area to exploit Sir Michael's nightly walking habit. Franklin Clarke explains that while the area near Chetton Fellows is usually quiet, the summer season brings many visitors to nearby Broadlands and Elbury Bay, making it easy for a stranger to blend in. The butler, Deverill, reports that no one came looking for Sir Michael yesterday and no suspicious persons were seen by the staff.\n\nFranklin introduces Tola Grey, Sir Michael’s secretary, who manages his correspondence. She confirms that Sir Michael received no letters with the initials \"ABC\" and has not mentioned seeing any loiterers. Croome leads the group to the site of the crime: a grassy ridge overlooking the sea, accessible via an abandoned path leading to Elbury Bay. Franklin describes the route Sir Michael took through the fields and back home. The group reaches the location where the body was discovered near a hedge, where Croome notes the victim was likely attacked while standing in the shade of a tree.\n\nUpon returning to the house, a doctor states that the death was instantaneous. Tola Grey expresses intense fear regarding the \"D\" in the ABC sequence, fearing the next murder. While Franklin expresses frustration with Poirot’s perceived incompetence, he mentions having a plan and wanting to consult the detective. Tola remains preoccupied with the whereabouts of the killer.",
